\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 5.2  Centering and Flushing\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Text can be centred on the page by putting it within the {\i0\scaps0\b0\f3 center} environment,\~and\~it\~will\~appear\~flush\~against\~the\~left\~or\~right\~margins\~if\~it is\~placed\~within\~the\~{\i0\scaps0\b0\f3 flushleft}\~or\~{\i0\scaps0\b0\f3 flushright}\~environments. Notice the spelling of {\i0\scaps0\b0\f3 center}\emdash unfortunately {\plain L{\up5\fs18 A}T{\dn7 E}X}{} doesn\rquote t understand the English spelling.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Text within these environments will be formatted in the normal way, in { particular the ends of the lines that you type are just regarded as spaces. To indicate a \ldblquote newline\rdblquote  you need to type the {\b0\i0\scaps0\f3 \\\\} command. For example: {{\par
